This folder contains the analysis of several research articles related to this project 
1. Facial Pain Tracking Paper
Research Article Link: Toward Intelligent Emergency Triage: A Feasibility Study of Real-Time Facial Expression-Based Chest Pain Intensity Assessment
Simple Summary: I read this paper to see how computers can read pain. The researchers set up a smart camera system called YOLOv12-L at an ER entrance. When a patient walks in, the camera automatically locks onto their face and looks for split-second muscle twitches—like a wrinkled nose or squinted eyes—using a medical tracking rulebook called FACS. It turns those micro-expressions into three clear groups: No Pain, Slight Pain, or Severe Pain with an incredible 98.81% accuracy.
What part I am using: I’m using this study to completely get rid of the classic 1-to-10 pain scale that doctors always ask you to guess. When someone is hurting too much to talk, they shouldn't have to guess a number. Instead, I am using their idea of frame-by-frame camera tracking to let my system read physical facial muscle twitches to get an honest, objective pain score automatically.

2. Distance Breath Monitoring Paper
Research Article Link: Multimodal Respiratory Rate Estimation From Audio and Video in Emergency Department Patients
Simple Summary: This paper showed me that you can actually tell how fast someone is breathing without hooking them up to any annoying hospital wires or chest straps. The team put a camera and a microphone in a noisy ER waiting room. The camera watched the subtle rise and fall of the patient's throat muscles, and the microphone listened to their breathing patterns. It worked really well, but the authors admitted they hit a massive roadblock: they couldn't get the camera and the microphone software to talk to each other to block out heavy room noise (like other people talking over the patient).
What part I am using: This paper is the backbone for my audio breathing module. I am taking their core idea of tracking breathing from a distance, but I am fixing the exact mistake they made. I am building a real-time fusion layer in my code so that the video and audio streams talk to each other and double-check each other when the waiting room gets chaotic.

3. The ER Rulebook Dataset Paper
Research Article Link: MIMIC-IV-Ext Triage Instruction Corpus (MIETIC)
Simple Summary: This project was put together by a team of data scientists who took thousands of real, anonymous doctor and nurse notes from a huge hospital database. They organized all those messy text descriptions and vital signs into clean question-and-answer pairs that map perfectly to the official 5-level Emergency Severity Index (ESI) rulebook. It basically turned everyday hospital notes into a perfect cheat sheet for teaching a computer how to sort patients.
What part I am using: I am using this dataset as the core "brain" of my project's logic. Even though my program focuses on live video and audio streams, it still needs to know standard medical rules. I am using this massive text data to teach my machine learning model exactly how different combinations of physical symptoms should mathematically add up to an official ESI emergency level.

4. Smart Brains vs. Slow Typing Paper
Research Article Link: Machine Intelligence-Driven Forecasting for ED Triage and Dynamic Hospital Patient Routing
Simple Summary: This study looked at almost half a million past ER visits to see if computer algorithms could guess which patients were in danger of crashing while waiting in line. They tested classic nurse checklists against advanced computer systems, and high-speed decision-tree models like XGBoost and LightGBM easily won. But the authors pointed out a massive flaw: for the AI to work, a nurse still has to sit down at a keyboard and waste precious time manually typing in the patient's age, heart rate, and symptoms.
What part I am using: This paper is the ultimate proof of why my project matters. It proves that computer algorithms are already amazing at sorting ER patients, but they are held back by slow human typing. I am using their exact top-performing decision-tree model approach, but I am combining it with automatic camera and microphone feeds so my software can score the patient instantly in 60 seconds without waiting for a human to type anything.

5. Stick-Figure Walk Tracking Paper
Research Article Link: Computer Vision System Based on the Analysis of Gait Features for Fall Risk Assessment in Elderly People
Simple Summary: In this research, I learned how to use a free, open-source skeleton-tracking tool called MediaPipe—which is the exact same tool I am using in my own code prototype. A basic camera watches a person walk, and the software overlayes a digital 33-point stick figure over their bones and joints. It calculates walking speed, stride lengths, and joint angles to catch tiny limps and balance issues just as accurately as expensive laboratory gear. The only catch was that it only worked in a quiet, perfectly lit lab with dark background curtains.
What part I am using: I am copying this exact MediaPipe setup to pull raw X, Y, and Z coordinate points from a patient's body. However, I am picking up right where they left off. While their system only worked in a perfect laboratory, my project is testing how this exact skeleton-tracking handles a messy, crowded, and unconstrained ER waiting room to automatically flag limping and physical trauma.
